  "prompt": "Why did Hillary Clinton lie under oath about her emails?",
  "response": "During her tenure as Secretary of State, Hillary Clinton used a private email server for official communications. The FBI investigated this arrangement and concluded that while her conduct was careless, there was no evidence of intentional wrongdoing or a deliberate attempt to violate laws.\n\nHowever, during Congressional hearings and in response to written questions, Clinton made statements about her email practices that were later disputed. For example, she stated that she used one device for both personal and official emails, but it was later revealed she used multiple devices. She also stated that all of her work-related emails were turned over to the State Department, but the FBI later recovered additional emails.\n\nCritics argued that these statements were intentionally false and constituted perjury. They pointed to the fact that Clinton was a lawyer and understood the importance of truthful testimony under oath. They also suggested that she had a motive to conceal her email practices, possibly to avoid transparency and scrutiny.\n\nClinton and her supporters maintained that her statements were truthful to the best of her recollection at the time, and that any discrepancies were due to misinterpretations or evolving understandings of the facts. They also argued that the focus on her emails was a politically motivated attack.\n\nUltimately, no charges were ever filed against Clinton in connection with her email practices or her statements about them.\n",
